annotation.TEXT: I is that glass block that you'd normally find a roulette item in.
Gulp!
Uh, oh! That bush has cutoff! This hack isn't going to be accepted at SMW Central!
A appears to be a turn block... that has multiple coins! Ooh, the possibilities...
And that's it for the Playground. Wow, that took longer than expected.
The next thing I want to show off is in the Where's Mario? level. First, let me go and find a blue koopa...
Well, just for hahas, let's see what happens...
N is some strange solid object.
So, who knows why that vine is there, but we've got some more doors to go through.
4 appears to be a green square that I can pass through.

Yep, jump #256 works normally as it takes the counter to 00/15, and then I can continue to jump normally for the next 15 jumps like usual. It's weird that it keeps counting and can rollover like that, when it appears to stop at 15/15.

Man, you didn't warn me that I could easily kill myself by placing an empty space over the solid ground I was standing on. Also, I gotta go through all that text again, and I can't skip it? That stinks. Fast-forward!
Hmm... I think this might just be a bonus world... What do you think?
And now I've got a key to take with me, but it can't be carried through doors, so I'll have to be a little clever...
Whoa, that's some rapid path creation there.
O... isn't doing anything... Oh, wait.
There's the balloon...
Q appears to be an entire fence gate, but once again, no climbing on it.
M is another brown used block... (Enough with the repeats!)

Aha, and there we go! The secret exit! Fortunately, the desync only forced me to redo this part of this level, because I typically record each level on a different movie file number. However, as a result, my stats will be slightly different at the beginning of the next level, as they reflect what I had after the first time I got this secret exit.
Alright, here's midpoint, and... umm... What's going on?
TAS in progress...
Ah, there we go. Now, normally in this level, if you try to jump or fly over the level, a ceiling stops you, like this.
Okay, let's start off with Grassland.
That's pretty interesting how that works. Oh, look at that. Is that a gray arrow sign?
Climb up here somehow to get this 1-up, and that's pretty much the only interesting thing here.
I think I'll just TAS most of these jumps so I can get to the rollover point faster...
Ha! I bet you thought I'd die there, even if only for a split-second. Am I right?
The koopa shell produced from this is a bit odd, though. It'll only show itself if you hit a nearby block or cape spin it to give it a thwack.
Well, I'm not surprised that desynched Mario managed to die to a goomba, but it's still silly.
Why'd the music reset? (That always bothers me when the music resets while transitioning between two areas with the same music in a hack.)
However, if I approach the beginning of the level again and retrigger that custom sprite, the ceiling will suddenly reactivate.
And of course, everything past R is disabled, so I get that "no good" sound.
And now to press Select, and... Well, that happened.
...And there's the wings. (Now, where's Yoshi when I need him?)
Well, that's not entirely true. Even though the counter appears to stop at 15/15, it's actually still counting each of your attempts to jump, and guess what happens if you "jump" 256 times?
And apparently, the shell makes the key turn invisible here.
Yes, laziness FTW!
But wait, the desynched footage continues and decided to reenter the level right away. I guess it wants another chance!
So, if you've wasted all of your jumps, and you don't mind mashing the jump buttons another 240 times, you can allow yourself to jump normally again without leaving the level!
Okay, now this time, maybe I'll try jumping as I'm trying to place an object.
However, this is about where the desynched footage ends, and I don't think that Goomba's coming back to kill me, so... yeah.
And is that a ? block that's near the gray arrow sign?
Ah, man, more text? I don't wanna have to read in a playground.
I can't climb on these things though.
C is an ordinary turn block. (I hope I'm getting close to some real power up blocks!)
To be continued...
Now, remember what I told you to remember last time? ...No? Well, then I'll show you again. Off to Toad's House!
Okay, so 1 and 2 create empty spaces, and 3 creates vines. That's kind of neat (though I don't know why 1 and 2 are the same).
And finally, we have the Cave.
K appears to be the left side of a pipe, while L appears to be the right side. Are there any pipe toppers, though?
And, I don't think there's anything else of interest here, but I'll climb around up here just to be sure...
Oh, yeah. Now that I've hit the Red Switch, I can easily get this 1-up by going through this door.
Moon count: 1
Okay, now before I go back to Forest of Doors like I intend to, there's a couple other things I want to show off in the earlier levels first.
Now, back to looking for the gray arrow sign...
Okay, now please remember to remember this message this time. A hidden door on the ? block near the gray arrow sign in Forest of Doors, eh? Let's go search for it.
...Hello! Now I can break the level this way all I want!
Demo count: 1

Makes me wonder why you'd advertise 256 values, and allow me to select any of them, but only allow up to R to be placed. If anything above R would crash the game, why not just stop me from cycling past R and only advertise those 28 values? Seems kind of weird...
There's your usual 1-up, but you have to go around and dig your way to it from above.
Yeah, take that, Goomba! For being desynched, that was pretty cool!
So next will be Mushroom Platforms.
Okay, moving on... B is a ? block with multiple coins.
Up next is the Castle.
Aw, man... That's mean alright.
However, that ceiling is actually generated by a custom sprite that's only placed at the start of the level, so if you use a reset pipe and then try to go off the top again...
Okay, so let's start looking for that gray arrow sign first. Also, I think I'll try to block clone me an extra power up or two if I can (since Colorful Coin Palace robbed me of my flowers).
Okay, I believe I'm done here.
Ouch! Mario, you idiot.
D is a brown used block. E, F, and G are all note blocks. Hmm, are any of those the "bounce on all sides" type?
Demo count: Still 1
It's probably towards the end of the level actually, like where you'd normally expect to see an arrow sign.
Moving on... 7 is... whatever that is. 8 is a mole hole.
Of course, why would I need these coins, since I can create as many as I want with value 6? Well, I'll collect them anyway.
...Just like that. OOHHH!!! MOOOONNN!!! Good thing I came this way!
9 appears to be a solid invisible block.
You know, I probably could've shell jumped over that wall... I should've tried that.
J is an ON/OFF block. Now, if only there were some guide-lines or other things to change with it... Also, I may as well grab this 1-up while I'm here.
So, let's play around in the Playground!
Hmm... P appears to be part of a fence gate, which strangely cuts off when placed in some spots (probably due to screen boundaries).
So, where could that gray arrow sign be? I'm pretty sure I passed by it on my first trip through the level...
H is a side-bouncing turn block that briefly looks like a P-switch as it's bouncing me.

Oh, I get it! O is what replaces a collected Yoshi coin, which is normally thin air, but if it overlaps something solid, you get an invisible ? block that'll contain either a key, wings, a balloon, or a koopa shell, depending on its X position.
Now, since you've already seen all of the placeable objects, I'm just primarily going to use number 3 (the vine) to explore these areas.
Well, I was thinking of doing the next level now, but I think I'll wait until next time!
Huh. This actually sounds interesting.
Okay, now to show off the other Playground areas. (And I'm going to cut out most of the text for your convenience.)
And now for jump #256...
And R seems to replace a couple of nearby solid tiles with invisible ? blocks, just like O does (and they contain the same things).
So, in Well-grounded, you get limited jumps, and after you've used your allotted 15, you can't jump anymore, right?

Okay, we're back! Sorry about all of that. Now, I'm resuming from about where the desync started really screwing me up, so all of that weird hopping around and that death to the Goomba basically never happened.
This one's got a bunch of coins to collect, along with the 1-up, which you have to dig to from above to reach again.
Well, aside from the extra reserve mushroom, the gameplay seems to be unaffected... Oh, well, whatever.
Yeah, that's all there is here.
And neither 1 nor 2 are hidden blocks as far as I can tell. They're just... nothing.
Huh. Now that's odd. When I did this recording, I completely failed to block clone at all and was stuck with just one mushroom. Did my recording desync?
Yay for experimentation!
Not anymore. It's a brown used block now, so I guess this isn't the secret... Actually, yes, this still is the secret. Just stand on the block and press up.
I don't remember acting this way when I was playing...
We now return you to our regularly scheduled SMW Hack.
Okay, so press Select to create an object... But, value 0 doesn't seem to do anything. Let's try changing the value to 1 by pressing R.
Actually, I think my recorded footage desynched again (or maybe this is a side effect from the previous desync that gave me the extra mushroom), and this time it's really screwed up my actions.
5 is an always spinning turn block, and... Ooh! 6 is a coin! Hey, if I position myself on a vine just right...
An invisible key block? But only after I placed O on top of something solid?
Yeah! I can become rich by just repeatedly hitting Select!
Okay, G appears to be the four-way bounce type, while E and F are vertical bouncing only.
Mario, are you on the drugs?
